BHP, ENRC, GlaxoSmithKline, Ryanair: U.K., Irish Equity Preview

-- B y   B l a n c h e   G a t t   a n d   S a r a h   J o n e s
-- 
2011-07-27T06:51:08Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-07-26/glaxosmithkline-rbs-group-ryanair-u-k-irish-equity-preview.html
The following is a list of companies
that may have unusual share-price changes in U.K. and Irish
markets. Stock symbols are in parentheses and prices are from
the last market close.  Futures on the benchmark FTSE 100 Index slid 0.2 percent to
5,878 at 7:50 a.m. in London. The FTSE 100 rose 4.47, or 0.1
percent, to 5,929.73 yesterday. The FTSE All-Share Index gained
0.1 percent to 3,085.14, while Ireland’s ISEQ Index retreated
0.9 percent to 2,890.19.  British American Tobacco Plc (BATS)  : The company
reported first-half adjusted operating profit of 2.76 billion
pounds ($4.53 billion), beating the median analyst estimate of
2.67 billion pounds. The shares rose 0.4 percent to 2,861 pence.  BHP Billiton Ltd. (BHP)  : The mining company has refused
to negotiate with striking workers at its Escondida facility in
Chile, the world’s largest copper mine. Strikes resumed at its
coking coal operations in Australia. The shares lost 0.9 percent
to 2,338.5 pence.  Eurasian Natural Resources Corp. (ENRC LN): The  Daily Mail 
reported that the company may soon be taken over by its major
shareholders for 1,200 pence a share. The newspaper didn’t cite
anyone. The stock advanced 1.3 percent to 791.5 pence.  GlaxoSmithKline Plc (GSK)  : The pharmaceutical company’s
Chief Executive Officer  Andrew Witty  said valuations on
acquisitions have “gone a little nuts” and that he would
rather give money back to shareholders than spend too much on
buying companies. The stock gained 0.7 percent to 1,373 pence.  ITV Plc (ITV)  : The U.K.’s biggest commercial broadcaster
said first-half revenue rose to 1.03 billion pounds from 987
million pounds a year earlier. That was in-line with the average
analyst estimate of 1.02 billion pounds, according to a
Bloomberg survey. The shares slid 0.6 percent to 68 pence.  Royal Bank of Scotland Group Plc (RBS)  : The U.K.’s
biggest government-owned lender hired David Havens as a credit
analyst from Nomura Holdings Inc. to boost the bank’s corporate-
debt team, according to two people familiar with the matter. The
stock declined 0.3 percent to 36.2 pence.  Ryanair Holdings Plc (RYA)  : Europe’s largest discount
carrier said Chief Executive Officer Michael O’Leary’s pay rose
to 1.04 million euros ($1.51 million) last year as his bonus
doubled. The shares fell 1.5 percent to 3.35 euros.  To contact the reporters on this story:
